          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Kurds ring a warning bell</h2> 
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-dec-25-1.jpg" alt="Kurds ring a warning bell" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The fall of Bashar al-Assad has left Syria vulnerable, with <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-dec-2024-1-kurdish-forces" target="_blank">Kurdish forces</a> fearing a revival of Islamic State groups as their focus shifts to defending against Turkish attacks. Prisons holding thousands of IS members are at risk, and detainees in camps believe they may be freed soon, potentially strengthening the group's revival.  Civilians in northeastern Syria face growing insecurity with fear of IS attacks and Turkish invasions. Kurdish leaders urge international intervention to prevent escalating chaos.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Turkey, who has a big hand in this transition, has focused on doing away with <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-dec-2024-2-international-support" target="_blank">international support</a> for Kurdish forces in Syria, such as the YPG, following the fall of Bashar al-Assad. Ankara regards the YPG as an extension of the PKK, which Turkey deems a terrorist group. Germany has <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-dec-2024-3-cautioned" target="_blank">cautioned</a> Turkey against escalating conflict with Kurdish forces in Syria, warning such actions could benefit IS and destabilize the region. Foreign Minister Annalena Baerbock emphasized the importance of Kurdish security and urged Turkey to avoid actions that might worsen violence. ​</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>


