          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Israel admits assassination</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Israel's Defense Minister, Israel Kat, <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-dec-2024-6-confirmed" target="_blank">confirmed</a> for the first time that Hamas leader Ismail Haniyeh was assassinated in a July operation in Tehran, Iran. Haniyeh’s death, attributed to an explosion, dealt a severe blow to Hamas during heightened tensions in the Middle East. Katz also highlighted Israel's broader operations targeting militant leaders and infrastructure across the region. It also further proves Iran's benefactorship of organizations like Hamas.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Katz <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-dec-2024-7-mentioned" target="_blank">mentioned</a> that Israel would “strike hard” at the Houthis and decapitate them while highlighting the killing of Yahya Sinwar and Hassan Nasrallah. Last week, the Houthis launched a missile attack on Tel Aviv as a retaliation for Israel’s airstrike in Yemen. The war between Hamas and Israel continues with many offers of ceasefire hostage deals struck down. </p>
        </mj-text>
    </mj-section>

